english:
  title: A Proclamation to the Island of Tsushima
  author: Byeon Gyeyrang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Let it be proclaimed:

    When Heaven brought forth this people, it endowed them with form through vital essence and bestowed upon them the principles of righteousness. Thus, those who cultivate goodness receive a hundred blessings, while those who commit wickedness incur a hundred calamities. In ancient times, the sage-kings revered the Way of Heaven. They taught their people to till the soil and plant the five grains, nourishing their bodies. They guided them according to their innate moral nature, perfecting their hearts. Should there arise those of stubborn and violent disposition who refuse to follow the Way—who covet wealth and slay others, showing no fear of death—then upon individuals falls punishment, and upon groups falls military expedition. Thus did Yao, Shun, and the Three Kings govern their people, and thus it has always been.

    The island of Tsushima, though situated in the sea and belonging to the Gyeongsang province, is rightfully part of Our realm, recorded in the historical chronicles for all to examine. Yet because its land is small and remote, surrounded by waters difficult to traverse, the common people have not dwelt there. Into this emptiness came the wretched Japanese—cast out from their own kingdom, having nowhere else to go. They established it as their lair. Seizing opportunities, they made raids upon Our peaceful subjects, plundering their wealth and grain, committing murders most vile. They have made orphans of children and widows of wives, burned homes to ash, perpetrating cruelty beyond measure for many years.

    Then came Our Grand Progenitor, the Great King Taejo, possessed of supreme benevolence and divine martial prowess. He responded to Heaven's mandate, brought forth a new age, and established the realm. The markets remained unchanged, yet the great enterprise was accomplished. Even the achievements of Tang and Wu could add nothing to this glory. The nation's power surged forth; military strength grew formidable. The realm pierced through seas and mountains, encompassing heaven and earth. All creatures with blood and breath trembled and submitted in that age.

    We commanded a general to eliminate the petty brigands of Tsushima—a task as effortless as Mount Tai pressing down upon an egg, or Benfu and Xiayu wrestling an infant. Yet Our Grand Progenitor, instead, extended the teachings of civil virtue and withdrew military might, displaying the way of grace and sincerity to bring them under Our benevolent rule.

    Upon inheriting the great inheritance and ascending to rule, We have faithfully upheld the will of Our predecessors, ever deepening Our care and solicitude. Though they have occasionally committed depredations and shown disrespect, We have remembered how the father of Dobu-ung-wa, Jeongmu, admired righteousness and offered loyalty. We have overlooked their transgressions. When their envoys arrived, We housed them with honor and commanded the Ministry of Rites to extend generous consolation. Considering their harsh circumstances, We permitted merchant vessels to trade, and rice and grain from Gyeongsan province have been transported to their island—tens of thousands of bushels yearly—so that their bodies might be sustained and they spared from hunger, their conscience refined so that they might be ashamed of banditry and live as others upon this earth. In this, Our diligence has been thorough.

    Yet they have repaid benevolence with betrayal, spurned righteousness, and sown the seeds of their own destruction. Nevertheless, those who previously surrendered and those who came for trade—indeed, all who have recently abandoned resistance—We have not put to the sword. We have settled them throughout Our provinces, providing food and clothing for their sustenance. We have also commanded Our border commanders to lead warships and encircle their island, awaiting their submission.

    Still they cling to their delusions. This troubles Us greatly. The island holds thousands of souls. We consider their livelihood and Our heart grows tender with compassion. Yet their island is mostly barren rock, lacking fertile soil where crops might grow. Unable to farm, they have turned to theft and brigandage. Their accumulated wickedness has reached its limit. In the unseen realm, the spirits of heaven, earth, and mountains send down calamities. In the visible world, Our magnificent horses, great ships, sharp weapons, and strong soldiers have established such thorough defenses by water and land that nowhere remains safe from Our judgment. Their only means of livelihood lies in fishing, gathering seaweed, and trade—yet in their betrayal and ingratitude, they have severed these paths themselves. This is not something We first severed; they have done it of their own accord. Losing these three ways, starvation awaits them, and they sit idle while death approaches.

    Yet consider this path forward: Should they suddenly awaken to remorse and contrition, should Dobu-ung-wa lead them in submission, We shall grant him noble rank and generous stipends. His subordinate officials shall be treated as the examples before them. The common people shall receive ample provisions and clothing, be settled in fertile lands where they might practice agriculture and gain its benefits, and be regarded and cherished equally with Our own subjects. Thus shall they understand that banditry brings shame and righteousness brings joy. This is the path to renewal, the way to livelihood. If they will not take this path, let them gather their people and return to their homeland—this too is acceptable.

    However, should they refuse to return to their own land, reject submission to Us, persist in their bandit schemes, and remain upon their island, then We shall prepare great fleets laden with provisions and encircle and assault that island. When time grows long, they shall perish from within. Should We further dispatch ten thousand chosen warriors to strike from all sides, not one shall escape. The children and women shall become food for crows and kites upon the earth, and fill the bellies of fish and turtles in the waters. Of this there is no doubt. Alas, is this not a cause for deep lamentation?

    Yet the paths to calamity and blessing lie clearly before them—these are not obscure matters beyond comprehension. The ancients said: "Calamity and blessing, all are sought from within oneself." They also said: "Even in a hamlet of ten houses, there shall be one person of loyalty and integrity." The people of Tsushima island, all possess by nature the capacity for goodness. Are there not among them those who can recognize the times and understand righteousness?

    Let the Ministry of War dispatch this proclamation to Tsushima, conveying Our deepest intentions, opening the path to renewal, that they might be spared the calamity of destruction, and thus fulfill Our purpose to cherish and protect all people.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Dobu-ung-wa (都都熊瓦): The Japanese ruler of Tsushima, whose father Jeongmu (貞茂) had previously shown loyalty to Korea.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''five grains'' (五穀) refers to the staple crops of East Asia: rice, millet, beans, wheat, and either hemp or corn depending on the tradition.'
  - key: ''
    value: Yao and Shun represent the ideal sage-kings of ancient Chinese legend; the 'Three Kings' (三王) typically refer to Yu, Tang, and King Wen.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Benfu (孟賁) and Xiayu (夏育): legendary strongmen of ancient China, used here as metaphors for overwhelming martial power.'
  - key: ''
    value: The proclamation employs the rhetorical strategy of offering incentives for surrender before threatening total destruction, reflecting classical diplomatic and military strategy.
